{{distinguish|James McQueen (disambiguation)}} '''James Macqueen''' (1778-1870) — sometimes '''MacQueen''' — was a Scottish geographer, statistician, political campaigner, pro-slavery and pro-Empire activist, banker and businessman, noted for founding the [[Colonial Bank (West Indies)|Colonial Bank]] and the [[Royal Mail Steam Packet Company]]. An expert on [[African geography]], he advocated the colonisation of that continent many decades before the so-called "[[Scramble for Africa]]" (1881-1914). He was co-owner and editor of the ''[[Glasgow Courier (Scottish newspaper)|Glasgow Courier]]''; wrote in London on politics, geography, economics, and general literature; and founded a bank in [[Mauritius]].
Although Macqueen had no academic education, professional training or qualifications, his amateur energy and enthusiasm, in several fields, made him a prominent, and controversial figure. He quickly lost interest in many of the projects he started. He had extensive correspondence with the [[Royal Geographical Society]], and many of his memoirs were published in its ''Journal'' and ''Proceedings''.
==Biography== Macqueen was born in [[Crawford, South Lanarkshire|Crawford]], [[Lanarkshire]], [[Scotland]], in 1778 and had become manager of a [[Sugar plantations in the Caribbean|sugar estate]] on [[Grenada]] by 1797. The [[British Admiralty]] postal [[sailing brig]]s were considered to be slow and unreliable by the colonial community, so on his return to Glasgow in 1830 he started a campaign for a [[steamship]] mail service to the [[West Indies]]. The government eventually decided to fund the project, and in 1839 the Royal Mail Steam Packet Company was granted a [[royal charter]]. In 1840 the Admiralty awarded it a contract to deliver mail to the West Indian colonies, with the first departure from [[Falmouth, Cornwall]], on 3 January 1842. The mail network expanded and the company operated services within the West Indies and to New York and [[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax]].
Macqueen died on 14 May 1870 at 10 Norton Street, [[Kensington]] (some sources say at Bury Street, [[St James, London|St James]]). He died, aged 92, in poverty, and his 59 year old widow Jean was forced to survive on charitable handouts from fellows of the Royal Geographical Society.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Racine|first1=Karen|title=The Human Tradition in the Atlantic World, 1500–1850|date=2010|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield Publishers|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=IOR5bOpGUiQC&pg=PA220&lpg=PA220&dq=macqueen+colonial+bank&source=bl&ots=eRPS6sRdtD&sig=HoH6pEHCHHv6YNFU_aldFgmk9Zg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwin7dXLsv3RAhXoFZoKHSbADLUQ6AEIHTAB#v=onepage&q=macqueen%20colonial%20bank&f=false}}</ref>
==See also== *[[Mungo Park (explorer)|Mungo Park]] *[[Mary Prince]] *[[Thomas Pringle]]
