'''Stocksundet''' is a [[strait]] in [[Stockholm County]] in [[Sweden]]. It connects the [[Edsviken]] sea inlet, to the west, with the [[Lilla Värtan]] strait and eventually the [[Baltic sea]], to the east. The strait also forms the border between the suburb of [[Stocksund]] in [[Danderyd Municipality]], to the north, and the suburb of [[Bergshamra, Solna|Bergshamra]] in [[Solna Municipality]], to the south. The strait is approximately {{convert|2|km}} long and varies in width between {{convert|90|m}} and {{convert|250|m}}, whilst its depth varies between {{convert|6|m}} and {{convert|15|m}}. 

Stocksundet is supposed to have received its name from the [[logging|log]]s (Swedish: "stock") which used to be laid out in the water to stop invading ships in the early Middle Ages. This name then led to the place name of ''Stocksund'', on the north side of the sound, and to the heraldry shield of the then Stocksund Municipality between 1955 and 1966.{{cite needed|reason=Looks like it has been translated by a previous editor from WP:SV, but that doesn't have a cite for this either|date=August 2017}}

By the 1400s, the road between Roslagen and Stockholm crossed Stocksundet, and by the 17th century, a [[ferry]] was provided. In 1716 the first bridge across the Stocksundet was built, principally to facilitate the movement of troops to the west in the event of an attack by [[Russia]]. Since then, there have been a total of seven bridges built across the strait.<ref name=Stocksund>{{cite web |url=http://www.lottero.se/Stockholm/danderyd.htm |title=Danderyd |language=Swedish |work=www.lottero.se |accessdate=27 August 2017 |archivedate=27 August 2017 |deadurl=no  |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170827155856/http://www.lottero.se/Stockholm/danderyd.htm}}</ref>

{{Multiple image|align=center|image1=Stocksundet - Bergshamra vattentorn.JPG|width1=350|image2=Stocksundet - Sikreno.JPG|width2=350|footer_align=center|footer=Stocksundet viewed from the south in 2012, showing (from left to right) the metro bridge, the road bridge and the new rail bridge. The remaining pier of the old rail bridge can just be seen at right.}} 

==Bridges==
[[File:Stocksundsbroarna 1934.jpg|thumb|The 1936 road bridge, seen with its 1826 predecessor and the 1885 railway bridge, viewed from the east]]
[[File:Neue Stocksundbrücke.jpg|thumb|The new railway bridge for the Roslagsbanan over Stocksundet.]]
From west to east, the strait is spanned by a bridge for the [[Stockholm metro]], a road bridge for the [[European route E18]], and a bridge for the [[Roslagsbanan]] narrow gauge commuter railway. Over time there have been seven bridges across the Stocksundet:

* The first bridge was built in 1716 the first bridge was built. It was a [[Pontoon bridge|floating bridge]] with a [[drawbridge]] that could be opened to allow boat traffic to pass. Despite needing frequent repairs, the bridge lasted until September 1824, when it was destroyed in a violent storm.<ref name=Stocksund/>{{sfn|Andrén et al.|2011|p=57}}

* In 1825-1826 a new {{convert|90|m|adj=on}} long bridge was built in five sections between stone [[Caisson (engineering)|caissons]] and including a [[swing bridge|swing section]]. The bridge was superseded as a road bridge with the opening of a new bridge in 1936, but remained in use a pedestrian and bicycle bridge until the winter of 1957/8. The land ends of the bridge are still visible, along with the bridge house.<ref name=Stocksund/>{{sfn|Stocksunds Köping|Folke Rengmark|1963|p=80}}<ref>{{cite book |title=Kulturmiljöhandbok för Danderyds kommun |volume=2:a upplagan |year=2003 |pages=167,166 |language=Swedish}}</ref>

* In 1885 a railway bridge was constructed to carry the [[narrow gauge]] [[Roslagsbanan]]. The bridge carried a [[Single-track railway|single track]], and was {{convert|98|m|adj=on}} long, and comprised two fixed spans of {{convert|36.6|m}} together with a {{convert|25|m|adj=on}} [[swing bridge|pivoting span]]. This bridge was replaced by a new bridge, on a different alignment, in 1996, and was demolished two years later. One of the bridge piers still exists within the stait, and the land ends of the bridge are visible.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.historiskt.nu/smalsp/srj/sr_j/sr_j_fakta.html |work=Historiskt |title=Järnvägshistorik: Linjen Stockholm Östra – Rimbo |accessdate=27 August 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170827164403/http://www.historiskt.nu/smalsp/srj/sr_j/sr_j_fakta.html |archivedate=27 August 2017 |deadurl=no}}</ref>{{sfn|Andrén et al.|2011|p=64}}

* Between 1934 and 1936, a modern [[concrete]] arch bridge was built a little further west than the 1826 road bridge. It had a span of {{convert|90|m}} and was {{convert|16|m}} wide, carrying two {{convert|1.5|m|adj=on}} walkways, two {{convert|2|m|adj=on}} bicycle lanes, and a {{convert|9|m|adj=on}} carriageway. This bridge had a relatively short life, and was replaced in 1990, being demolished in order to make way for its replacement.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://runeberg.org/tektid/1936v/0067.html |title=Technical Journal / 1936. Road and Water Engineering |work=Project Runeberg |accessdate=27 August 2017 |language=Swedish}}</ref>{{sfn|Andrén et al.|2011|p=59}}

* In 1978 a bridge was built to carry the extension of the [[Stockholm metro]] to [[Mörby centrum metro station|Mörby centrum station]]. The bridge is {{convert|240|m}} long, and consists of a four-span curved concrete structure, with a navigation clearance of {{convert|13|m}}. The bridge carries twin tracks, and the line runs in tunnel at each end of the bridge.{{cite needed|reason=I translated this from WP:SV, which uses a cite of ''Eniro sjökort'', but I cannot locate this|date=August 2017}}

* By the 1980s, the 1936 road bridge was no longer able to carry the increasingly intensive road traffic, and it was decided to replace it with two new parallel bridges for the Norrtälje road (E18) (one for north and one for south-traffic). The first of these bridges was completed in 1990, enabling the 1936 bridge to be demolished to make way for the second new bridge, which opened in 1992. The bridges have two large and one small span each, with the largest span of {{convert|122|m}}, with a navigation clearance of {{convert|12|m}}. The bridges are respectively {{convert|15.5|m}} and {{convert|19.5|m}} wide, carrying three northbound and four southbound lanes, together with pedestrian and cycle facilities.{{sfn|Andrén et al.|2011|p=59-61}}

* In 1996 a new railway bridge was built for the Roslagsbanan, located {{convert|100|m}} west of the 1885 bridge, as part of the reconstruction of the line to [[Double-track railway|double track]]. The new alignment necessitated the relocation of [[Stocksund railway station|Stocksund station]]. The new bridge was designed by architect {{ill|Laszlo Marko|sv}} and is a concrete structure with four spans. It is {{convert|215|m}} long and has a navigation clearance of {{convert|8|m}}, somewhat lower than the adjacent road and metro bridges.{{cite needed|reason=I translated this from WP:SV, which uses a cite of ''Eniro sjökort'', but I cannot locate this|date=August 2017}}

